media.plainText: Transcendentalism

A philosophy founded in Northeastern America in the early 1800's, borrowing from ideas of Immanuel Kant. Stresses that people can only reach their highest potential when they rise above, or transcend, the expectations & limitations that society & institutions place on them.
Dogma
Any system or way of thinking that is widely accepted as truth because it has been laid down long ago by an authority.
Bracketing
The process of setting aside assumptions about things & looking at them with fresh eyes.
New Age
A contemporary philosophy that stresses higher spiritual awareness on a global level. Emphasizes global awareness and incorporating any number of multi-cultural beliefs and styles.
Metaphysical
Means beyond the physical. A branch of philosophy that studies reality in general. To believe in the metaphysical is to believe in things that can't be proven or observed with the five senses.
Asceticism
The practice of denying oneself physical comforts & necessities to focus on things other than the material world.
Collective Unconscious
In the psychology of Carl Jung, the body of symbolism & mythic images inherited from early humans that people have in their unconscious minds. (Akashic Records...?)
Marxism

A 19th century philosophy based on the principles of Karl Marx. Says that the way people think depends on the way that people make & use things. A person's sense of self-worth is determined by their usefulness in society.
Feminism
A philosophical & political movement that stresses gender equality in a male-dominated society. First emerged during the French & American revolutions, then again in the US in the 1960's.
Monotheism
The belief in a single all-powerful God. Judaism, Christianity, & Islam all fit into this category.
Pantheism
Means all is god. That belief that God is all things and all things are God. Includes a belief that people are aspects of God & therefore have divine power in themselves.
Mysticism
The idea that we can have direct contact & personal experience with God without a mediator (priest, minister, etc.). This may come through dreams, visions, meditation, or art.
Pragmatism
A philosophy founded by C.S. Pierce & William James that says the meaning of anything depends on its practical applications.
Existentialism
A philosophy supported by Kierkegaard, Heidegger, Sartre stressing that individuals are free and give their own meaning to reality.
Epicureanism
An ancient Greek philosophy founded by Epicurus in the third century BCE. Stresses the avoidance of mental pain, stress, & anxiety by seeking simple pleasures. (Enjoying the simple things in life.)
Skepticism
The view that we can't be certain of anything. It comes from an Ancient Greek word meaning, "seeking."
Stoicism

An ancient Greek philosophy founded by Zeno in the third century BCE. Stresses emotional detachment from the workings of fate and to live in harmony with divine Reason. Teaches indifference to fortune, pleasure, or pain.
Ataraxia
The ancient Greek term for mental tranquility.
Arete
The ancient Greek term for the highest personal excellence & integrity to do what must be done. Fulfillment of one's life's purpose.
Akrasia
The ancient Greek term for weakness of will that causes people to do what they know is not right.
Materialism
The belief that existence is only physical. Thinking & knowing are effects produced by our senses. (Basically, that there is no soul. All that exists is matter and energy.)
Dualism

The belief that reality can be separated into both material & spiritual components. The spiritual component makes thinking & knowing possible. (The spirit world exists, and is separate from the physical world.)
Confucianism
A philosophy of ancient China founded by Kung fu-tzu that stresses social harmony & respect for others.
Li
The Chinese word for courtesy & ceremoniousness. Confucius used the term to bring ritual & respect to daily life.
Buddhism
A philosophy/religion founded in India during the 5th century BCE by Siddhartha Gautama. Stresses that suffering happens when we don't get what we want, so we should stop wanting so much.
Nirvana
The ultimate goal of Buddhism. The release from suffering, release from desire, and release from a sense of self.
Taoism
An ancient, mystic Chinese religion based on the writings of Lao Tzu. Means "the way." Stresses acceptance of the way things are & union with the nature of the world.
Wu-wei
Means, "non-doing." A Taoist principle that means receptivity, acceptance, and effortless action.
Yin & Yang
A Taoist symbol that represents the balance of opposing forces.
Feng Shui

A Taoist form of divination sometimes called "geomancy" (Earth Magic). Practitioners believe that the positions of geological features and natural elements can affect the well-being and good fortune of people that live in the area. Applies to building a home, furnishing & decorating a home, and even selecting a burial site. Translates to "wind water."
Hinduism
An ancient Indian religion based on our duties and action. It includes the belief in reincarnation and has a large pantheon of gods & goddesses.
Dharma
According to Hinduism, our duties we must fulfill to the gods, our families, or neighbors, & ourselves.
Karma
According to Hinduism, the sum of our actions, & actions in previous lives, that determine the fate of our future existence.
Moksa
In Hinduism, the transcendent release from suffering. The Hindu equivalent of nirvana. Includes the release from the karmic cycle of reincarnation.
Ahimsa
The Hindu & Buddhist principle of nonviolence that encourages respect for all living things.
Yoga
A form of mental & physical discipline that many Hindus believe can lead to moksa.
Chi

In many cultures this is the breath of life. It is the life force that flows through the universe and all living things. It is your own personal energy and connection to the universe. Chinese = Chi, Japanese = Ki, Hindu = Prana, Ancient Egypt = Ka, Jediism = The Force.
Deism
The belief in an unknowable God who set the world in motion at the beginning of time, but has done little to interfere since that time.
Monism
The belief that the natural world is all connected into a single, unified whole. There is only one thing - the universe. All other divisions are artificial and arbitrary.
Ethics
The study of moral & social behavior. Our actions should not only benefit us, but benefit our society. Just because we can do something doesn't mean we should.
Relativism
The idea that good & bad are not universal, but may be different in different societies.
Ontology
The metaphysical study of being & existence.
Epistemology
The study of knowing. What do we mean when we say that we "know" something?
Empiricism
The idea that we can only be certain of knowledge acquired through our senses. In other words, reality is produced by experience.
Rationalism
The epistemological position that we can have knowledge of things without having experienced them.
Cosmogony
The study of the origin of the world. (More scientific.)
Cosmology
The study of the nature & order of the world. (More metaphysical and spiritual.)
Microcosm
The idea that a person is a reflection of the whole world.
Macrocosm
The idea that the whole world is a reflection of a person.
Reincarnation
In Hinduism and Buddhism, the process by which a soul is reborn continuously until it achieves perfect understanding
